text: There are only so many times you can get away with being "just fun". I will, hand-on-heart, defend the 2009 movie to my dying day. It was fine then because they were getting a foot in the door to revamp the franchise, they gave us an enjoyable ride and set the stage for weightier, more faithful installments to come thereafter (with the whole alternate timeline idea), but now it's almost 2016 where we *do* have the kind of fun space adventures Star Trek 09 was initially making up for the lack of. Now in a world where Guardians is a huge hit with audiences, and Star Wars is returning in a couple days, it's time to let Star Trek be Star Trek. I'll go for the cast, I'll go for the action, I'll go for the visuals, I'm sure I'll even enjoy myself..  But it's time we accepted it; this isn't Star Trek and these filmmakers clearly have no interest in it being so. That's a big shame.

text: I can't believe THIS (bullshit!) is what is being released for Star Trek's 50th Anniversary.  Tried to restrain judgment, but I can't.  Not after the first 25 seconds and seeing Her Majesty The Enterprise destroyed and abandoned by her crew and captain.  The only acceptable time destroying the Enterprise occurs is in The Search for Spock.  This...I have no hope, none.  Star Trek is not about action and explosions.  Star Trek is about exploration, peace, science, intelligence, and (above all) the characters.  Everyone involved with this reboot seems to have either forgotten that, or deliberately ignored it.

text: Epic new Star Trek trailer. It looks awesome... some Star Trek fans will be angry about that, but at least Star Trek is still alive. I completely understand the fear of popularising the franchise, but Star Trek fans have to do the sums. The new Star Trek films have increased the fanbase by between 30 to 50% which means that the films will continue to be made, however, the fanbase remains small enough that Star Trek is still the least popular of all the current cinema franchises. Don't worry Star Trek fans, the average person on the street still thinks that you are sad for liking Star Trek, which is a wonderful thing. Embrace it.  I know I do...and i say that as someone who has been a fan of the films for the last 25 years.

text: Star Trek isn't supposed to be all action-y. Seriously, in the original series there was action from time to time but they didn't base whole episodes around it. As a kid I always thought of Star Trek as a more peaceful version of Star Wars, the occasional war here and there but that was it. There were loads of new discoveries, new planets, new races and new cultures; here we get some of the new planets, races and cultures but we had enough war and action in the last two films.  What is it with these movies and constantly destroying the Enterprise?  This is not Star Trek, this is someone trying to compete with the action in his other films.

text: Star Trek lost director JJ Abrams to Star Wars unfortunately and that may hurt the reboot that started off brilliantly. Star Trek is a show steeped in history spanning four decades and has a huge fan following that doesn't want films that are not 'star trekky'. The Enterprise may be destroyed in this film but the series is actually about the 'family' that forms the crew. Star Trek isn't about just action, it has a definite tone of voice and ethos, and the success of these films will depend on how well they get the balance of sci-fi legend with modern day fast and furious CGI right.

When were suppose to be wrapping up a trilogy, meaning there was a beginning, a middle, and this my fans is the end. So  how is it that were at the end of a trilogy and i'm scratching my head on WTF is going on. text: *Why isn't this Star Trek.. I would honestly love if you wrote your main reasons..* -The team is back in space, at the far reaches.. (classic) -The film takes place stranded on an alien planet (classic) -Everyone is getting in on the adventure, instead of just Spock (classic) -The villain is something new, and exciting instead of Human (classic)   I think the fun, action packed trailer is what ruins it for some people... granted this is our first look at the movie... the 2nd trailer for all we know might be dark, with an epic score... this is meant to grasp people seeing STAR WARS (the darkest, most epic film of the year) They want audiences to think, HEY that looks fun! I love the Star Trek films!  Star Trek Darkness (which I think is F'n amazing, and underrated) was very dark.. nothing like the fun ride we had in 2009.. this is going back to that... with Pine, and Quinto confirmed for Trek 4 I think this is a perfect time to be fun, and have a good time, while having a terrifying villain (Idris Elba looks sick awesome).. and then return to an extremely dark, extremely serious film in the sequel Star Trek 4 (Klingon war maybe?)  *The only thing I'm upset about is the absence of Alice Eve <3 Carol Marcus...* I was extremely excited to see Kirk/Carol relationship further explored (pun intended)... hopefully they say what happened to her... and bring her back for Trek 4.

text: it's called star TREK! The morons left out the TREK!  Gene Roddenberry before he passed, there's even behind the scenes interview with him on Next Generation here on YouTube when it began, he said he wasn't sure where Next Gen would take us, but the #1 rule is there must be a Trek. It carries mankind's innate instinct to explore! to go where no man has gone before! what's out there? He set clear rules for the entire franchise the #1 rule that can't be broken is there must be a trek, exploration. I would almost believe if Gene were alive today he'd never allow this crap and the last couple crappy next gen movies to be made.  for all its flaws First Contact should have been the last, we got to see the creation of what became the federation, and took care of Borg. Gene's best villain he ever created. The early Borg were badass scary. After Gene died and the Queen introduced it "humanized" the Borg and fucked them up.   course that's my opinion.

Even the Borg were done well (though that came pretty close a few times).  This modern "odds massively against us" stuff... it's just turning me off. text: What the fuck did I just watch? ...  So I've had a few minutes to digest this; rather than anger, this trailer literally made me sad because I know for sure that no new Star Trek movie or show will ever again be made with Star Trek fans in mind. The first one was fun, but was more Star Wars than Star Trek. Into Darkness was just a mashing of previously used Star Trek ideas stuffed into remake wrapping paper and was less Star Wars and more Action Movie in Space.  I'm not afraid of change, or something new. Give me something new. But think of it like this:  What if Star Wars were made to into a dry, political drama in which Jedi were little more than diplomats being sent out on missions to settle trade route negotiations, characters with no personalities and muddled motivations were to take the place of a coherent story, and real sets and characters were to be replaced with sterile, green-screened recreations of the people and places they were meant to depict? Who the fuck would want to see that?

text: I’m worried!!  If this trailer isn’t just a decoy (like Batman’s nightmare on BvS trailer), my guess is that this movie will be the end of the franchise… but I honestly want to believe this is just a joke from Simon Pegg… and the movie has a completely different tone… For other fans (like me ) who loved the original series and the next generation, I have a few questions: 1 -Why show us the destruction of the Enterprise? (I’m not comfortable  with that) 2 – Why ground the crew on a planet... to face different challenges and adventures?  (I’m still waiting for the regular adventures… “Space the final frontier” isn’t that the promise?) 3 – Who are those aliens? The visual reminds me more like SciFi’s Defiance mixed with Babylon 5 4 – Doesn’t it feel like Star Trek Generations (or Insurrection)?… if so? Isn’t that bad for business?

How about solving problems, that isnt just about shooting and killing stuff. text: Judging from my guess of the plot and the handful of scenes shown, it's possible that this is the closest movie to a TOS episode we've ever seen.   It seems as if they're exploring deep space, encounter some kind of crazy swarm that attacks the ship, and the crew ends up forced to crash-land somewhere by this mystery swarm. They run into some other unknown aliens who have suffered the same fate and with no resources have to try and figure out the mystery. Through cooperation, diplomacy, and heroic action they eventually save the day despite limited resources. That's pretty damn TOS sounding. I wouldn't be surprised though if the aliens turned out to be maybe humans from the future in some kind of weird time travel plot twist or something. Too few details given to really tell.  The music and editing makes this seem like a modern day Guardians of the Galaxy type of popcorn action film, but given the trailer's presence in front of Star Wars I'm sure they're just hyping it up for a mainstream audience. That's not the type of trailer I really wanted to see, but given the financial realities here I get it. Hopefully in a month or two once Star Wars hype dies down a bit they'll have a second extended trailer that gives a better sense of the film.  Extremely cautious about this, but actually a tiny bit optimistic as there might be a decent number of TOS elements here.

text: To all those people who are complaining about this movie, be thankful that there is even a movie that somewhat relates to Star Trek.  TMP sucked, Search for Spock wasn't great, The Final Frontier was a joke, Insurrection bombed,  Nemesis seemed like a rushed way to send off the TNG crew, then TV Shows... DS9 was a little too preachy, Enterprise mucked things up and just as it was getting good it got killed unceremoniously.    Unfortunately Star Trek in it's original intended form is not a money maker and studios only care about money - they don't care what Roddenberry's vision was.  They aren't going to drop a dime on anything that they don't think will make money and as much as it hurts fans to admit it, the Star Trek movies prior to this JJverse reboot/refit/remake/sequel series weren't money makers and were not well received by anyone other than Trek fans which in the eyes of the studio mean limited return on investment.   I watch the old stuff in the comfort of my home no problem and enjoy it, but I'll take these Action movies even if you could essentially replace the costumes and character names and end up with a Guardians of the Galaxy movie - which would still be awesome.  Take what you can get - or just go off and watch the Stupid looking remake of Ghostbusters with a crappy 80s Ectomobile, Stupid looking proton packs strapped onto the cast of Bridesmaid.  (Funny actresses who I do like, but I'm having a hell of a time seeing them as Ghostbusters)   Oh and if you don't like the JJverse, at least you can be satisfied that the enormously oversized Enterprise which dwarfed Galaxy class ships appears to be destroyed in this one.

text: Movies are meant to look good through trailers. If you want to create any hope of having people be interested in your movie, you need to make a trailer that at least seems somewhat appealing to the viewer. This trailer was horribly edited. I am a filmmaker and an editor myself, and I can easily tell you that whoever made this trailer knew nothing about what they were doing.   For one, the music. The music fits horribly for this trailer. It's not bad music, but it just doesn't help to set things up. Maybe for another one they could've done something with it. It's not necessary that they set the film up with a dark tone or something like that. The trailer should've been longer (two minutes, no less) and set up the film more.  Speaking of which, that's the second problem -  the trailer is so short. It sets up nothing about the film and only leaves the viewer confused - that's exactly how I feel right now. Granted, they shouldn't give away the entire film, like the Batman vs. Superman trailer did. But here they just didn't buff up the trailer enough. It's a complete hit and miss. And lastly, as of now, the movie just doesn't look good. The opening of the trailer could've been a buildup to something bigger, but the entire thing wound up being a bunch of random action shots that amounted to nothing. So that's why a third of the ratings are dislikes, because it is most certainly a horrible trailer.

text: Star Trek was a vision by Rodenberry. He believed  that everyone will be able to live a life in peace  in the future. And as if we don't aleready have enough violence and conflicts on earth, we even need to make this franchise more violent with generic action and fighting. I saw a documentary featuring a guy from motorola saying that Star Trek inspired him to create the first mobile phone. A generic action based plot with an established IP  built around it won't accomplish something so awesome like that. And to anyone who says: Well Star Trek wasn't for everyone and now they wan't everyone to be able to enjoy it. Well then someone is doing his job wrong, I think it's possible to produce an interessting/intelligent movie most people enjoy! It's not easy, but if you can accomplish that you have created a piece of art not an generic commercial throaway product. The team behind it deserves a price for turning our society even more stupid.

text: Star Trek, at its core, was about (1) ideas, morality and what it means to be human, (2) well-defined likable characters with a lot of chemistry between them,  (3) high concept sci-fi plots with a dash of action and humor, and (4) hope for the future. The last movie was enjoyable, but it wasn't Star Trek. The problem, quite simply, is it's not clear anymore what ST is, should be, or should say, in today's society. But there's no way Paramount will let a franchise die when there's a built-in fan base and money to be made. They'll pander to whoever they have to get the asses in the seats, even if they franchise is philosophically adrift.

text: There's a lot of hate showing up for this way too action oriented film. I agree, this seems like way too much for Trek. But I have to say, something that I disliked very much about the last two films were how much they seemed to just take place on, or near, earth. I craved seeing them explore to find NEW WORLDS and NEW CIVILIZATIONS and this film, finally addresses that. There appears to be no bastardization of an older plot-line. This is essentially just a single episode of the original show, turned into a movie. With way too much action. I have more hope for this film than it seems like most other do.

text: It does finally seem at least less villain-focused than the past three films. It looks a bit more like it's shooting for something along the lines of Insurrection or Star Trek V, in that we do get to see an alien civilization and some kind of revolt perhaps, though hopefully better executed than in those films. It looks lighter and a bit more problem-solving than villain-killing, so it looks promising. I'm cautiously optimistic that this might finally feel a bit more like TV Trek, but with movie Trek action and over-sized emotion.  I noticed Orci, McKay, and Payne are still listed as writers.  Perhaps there influence is still there, including Orci's wish that the film move away from villains.  I hope Elba's playing more of an antagonist that meets Kirk halfway, and it ends in a truce with both sides having a better understanding of the other, like in the best Trek stories.

text: So....I actually liked the first two J.J Abrams Star Trek movies, even though yes, they did stray a bit from the original feeling of Star Trek...but this sort of makes me feel like J.J Abrams should have stayed with directing it, cause even though there is one thing that's pretty cool and right about this movie (the fact their seemingly spending a lot of time on a strange planet trying to escape and all that and Kirk is spending a lot of time with some alien girl. That fits specifically with the original Star Trek show lol) BUT, if the whole movie is too action-y, which this trailer is making it look like, that would totally take away from the Star Trek feel. A good amount of action, sure, but it can't be like your usual summer action blockbuster lol And THEN we have Sabotage by Beastie Boys playing throughout the ENTIRE trailer! I love the song myself, but playing it for more than a bit in a Star Trek trailer takes away from the feel AGAIN. Ugh...let's hope this is all because the TRAILER was mad kinda badly for any sort of "fan" of Star Trek, and not the whole movie. Let's hope for it to be a marketing ploy, guys, come on! Don't lose hope! XD

author: Scott Ballard

text: I'm surprised that the movie will probably be, or at least looks, more "intimate." That is a positive. I don't have a problem with a action, however this doesn't even feel like Star Trek. I'm just hoping the silly marketing is covering up something special.  My biggest problem is that after two films I still don't give a crap about the characters. Why would i care about them doing anything now? This is why star trek died more than a decade ago, the characters became secondary to the plot. The bad thing is that this film might be great and no one will see it because in the last film Spock of all people decided to punch his emotions out.  Star Trek is a great franchise that i love, but it doesn't have the strength of Star Wars, nor its blind fan,s to endure complete madness and survive. Of course the first Avengers trailer was terrible too and the second made it amazing. We will see.

They are probably fighting the planets auto defense system or they are fighting a race that attacks everything that comes near so they can steal their technology.  I can get with the story line.  But they could of picked a better director.  5 big budget movies to his credit, and none of them are very good.  But maybe it will be good, I'm sure I will watch it and probably enjoy it. text: I'm gonna go into this film with neutral expectations. I've always found that the best way to watch a film is to go in with neutral expectations. If you go in with high expectations then you're just gonna focus on all of the good things and not even acknowledge the bad (case in point; most marvel movie fans. Most, not all of them), and if you go into it with low expectations you're going to only focus on the bad things and not even make an attempt to acknowledge and/or enjoy the good things about it. My point is, don't judge until it comes out and then when it does just give it a chance instead being irritatingly negative or too praising.

text: Feelings for this trailer. . . well they're finally off planet. That's a plus, but it doesn't have a star trek feel. The first two movie trailers weren't action packed and it still held a certain, awe to it. This trailer, with the music choice (which might be why I feel this way), kind of makes me feel like I should put on some leather, grab a couple guns and get ready to kick some a$$. Not something I should feel when watching Star Trek. Especially since I avoid action movies due to the redundancy (unless it's marvel). I will reserve final judgment. There's a lot of trailers that show all the actiony parts in the trailer and the rest of the movie doesn't have that. So it's possible that this is one of those times. Also with lowered expectations, I might enjoy it more. But I went into Darkness (I know a lot of people hated that one) with high expectations, and I loved it so much, I got into TOS.  Til now I held the reboot and TOS separate  in my likes. The main reason being that the reboot had yet to go on the five year mission and doing its own thing. This is changing that. Lets pray, they don't screw it up.

text: This  is it.  Star Trek fans need to unite and do something.  The "don't watch it" is the only weapon left in the Trek fandom to stop these embarrassments. They harm the franchise by reducing the value and message of what Star Trek is to a younger audience.  I know from the conventions Star Trek fans are upset about the current films. There are not enough "young new" fans to bring in the money Paramount expects or needs to keep making these movies; the success of these movies still depends upon the long term Star Trek loyalists. The last movie barely broke even for what the studio spent. I know the feeling of obligation, we Star Trek fans feel, to to see everything Trek. But, at a minimum, stay away for the first two weeks of release. This is the period the studio makes the most money, without sharing with the theaters. text: Every line in this trailer seems to be either a platitude or a quippy one-liner followed by an explosion, and it's giving me second-hand embarrassment.  This one, like its two predecessors, seems to be another punishment of Ex$plo$ive Blockbu$ter $chlock.  Star Trek used to be defined by its interest in social reform, non-violent problem solving, and publicly approachable philosophy.    The Original Series had the first ever nationally televised interracial kiss, TNG challenged gender norms by having men wear mini dresses and by writing episodes with obvious LGBT parallels, Voyager made a point to include a richly diverse cast and a female captain, DS9 had a black commander, a gender fluid main character, and often wrote episodes that explored the devastation and aftermath of war.    Meanwhile, the new movies have a whopping total of two people of color in the main cast, a white-washed Kahn, three total named female characters who have lines (all of whom have appeared partially naked).   Zero gay couples, zero trans people, zero disabled characters, and a huge emphasis on violent "problem solving". I can't believe it's 2015 and this huge budget series is ethically straggling behind a schmaltzy TV show written in the 60s.  Star Trek is supposed to be political and intelligent, so if you don't want to make a Star Trek movie, then stop pretending to make them.

text: To anyone saying "It's trying to be fresh and inclusive for the younger audiences, and make a profit":  Take a look at Star Trek: First Contact.  First Contact had action. Five minutes in, and we're already seeing a Borg Cube taking out ships by the second. Then we see a bombing, a firefight, a fight aboard a starship, another firefight, etc. We even see Picard with a goddamn tommy gun.  But the thing was, First Contact also had a story, and nuanced messages. We got two new, dynamic characters introduced, we got backstory for the world we know and love, we learned old flaws of our favorite characters, and we felt for them. They did action, they did science, they did drama, and *NONE OF IT WAS BORING*. It was a smart movie, but like this, it was accessible to everyone as long as they knew the characters.  Everyone loved it. It's still the 4th-highest-grossing Trek movie yet, including the reboots, and it almost made double its budget. The film buffs enjoyed the direction and themes, the mass audience ate up the action, and the nerds had all the technobabble and continuity they could want.  It's too early to judge Beyond, but it just seems generic and dumbed-down, even for the reboot. The trailer has a couple cool shots, and the bit with Bones is pretty funny, but that's all I'm seeing. I'm not mad about it, but I'm getting tired of what we're getting, and I think the audiences are too.

And while I like Justin Lin as an action director, I don't feel that a Star Trek film needs to have the look and feel of a "Fast and Furious" flick. I think Paramount needs to realize that Star Trek will never be a box office phenomenon, and just let the franchise be more Trek, than Wars. text: Good god, what is with everyone hating on this? I think it looks fine. Star trek has always had humor in it, and sometimes there are some goofy or silly moments, but that's what makes it great too. The last two movies were very serious, and I'm sure this one will still be, but what's wrong with it being a little lighter this time? And what's wrong with it being like Guardians of the Galaxy anyway? That movie was awesome! To me it reminds me of TOS, and if you like that, then this I think pays some homage to the more comedic side of Star Trek.  Just putting in my opinion.

text: I'm thinking this is a Xindi storyline (Enterprise). The alien ships at 1:00 look very similar in design to Reptilian Xindi ships, just smaller. The white female alien could very well be a Primate Xindi (the way her hair is style is a bit similar to how theirs was in Enterprise). And the alien at 1:10 could potentially be an Arboreal Xindi. The swarm-like attacks could indicate some kind of Insectoid Xindi tactic. Didn't see any Aquatics or Aerials.  Almost certainly a Xindi storyline. It looks like maybe in this timeline there is some kind of Xindi Civil War? Perhaps the Reptilians (and maybe Insectoids) are now attacking Earth, after subjugating the other Xindi species.
author: Mr. Mayhem

text: You know, I've made this argument a million times and I've made this argument since the first reboot movie. The original Star Trek films are old and slow, sure, us old school Star Trek fans love those shows and SOME of those movies, but take off your rose-tinted nostalgia glasses for one fucking second and think; think for one goddamn second that an old style Star Trek movie would alienate a ton of viewers that want a fun summer action movie. They don't want to bring in entirely old audiences, they want new people to start loving the series as well, so why can't you be fucking happy that this series is acting as a gateway for new fans? But you know what? If you want Star Trek to die by confusing new fans with a slow ass pace and a boring movie, you go right ahead but me, personally, I want Star Trek to live on and get more and more popular. So if you don't like the new Star Trek, shut the fuck up and go watch TNG for the billion and first time. (And Sabotage was in the first Star Trek reboot so stop bitching)
author: Clutch545

text: Dear producers and marketing staff, why do you have to change good things into not good things? text: For all the haters who've never really grasped what the creators of the tv series ever tried to do... yes, Star Trek isn't originally heavy on epic action-ness... but you have to wonder if the only reason that was the case was because it was the 60s and they just weren't able to pull off scenes like in these new movies. Technological resources for big budget action were very scarce, and it's even been openly admitted that a lot of the tv show (especially the first have of season 1) was met with a lot of close calls deadline-wise (i.e. The Menagerie parts 1 and 2 being the saving grace period that allowed them to catch up with the project, look it up). I wouldn't be entirely convinced if someone tried to tell me that Gene Roddenberry would be terribly opposed to having JJ Abrams and/or Justin Lin.  Just sayin'.

text: and the dumb down of the franchise continues..Gene Rodenbbery's orginal vision of the Star Trek universe was one of optimism, of cooperation, and cerebral content that asked the big questions. Action and gratuitous violence was always secondary to a good plot and intelligent character development. This started in TOS and continued with TNG, DS9, and even Voyager...Then Paramount decided to hire new script writers with the intent of capturing the 12-24 demographic...and we are left with a shell of how cutting edge, controversial and cerebral the original franchise was. Ironically there are many more people that are Trek fans that are NOT in that "magic" demographic..and if the braintrust at Paramount would understand that, well they might instead make a movie that surpasses, dare I say it, the popularity of Star Wars...

text: Ok, movie trailer editor guy-  basic lesson in film tone:  The score over the imagery will always have a dramatic impact on the way something is perceived.    You want to attract people with an intriguing mystery? Leave the score silent and dub some eerie dialogue from the movie over your cuts.    You want to convey a "this might be the END" vibe?  Stick with low tones, sweeping cello and bass, or go the Inception route and do the plunging BWAAAAAAA's over epic wide angle shots.    You want to show that your movie is just a mindless action romp they won't remember the next day?  That's when you slap 8,000 action shots together in quick succession and dub over everything with an extraordinarily cliche pop song.  This is basic shit, guy.  So I have to assume you put this laughable "teaser" together in this way because there wasn't enough substance in the film to convey any other tone.  If I'm wrong, prove it Paramount.

text: Everyone complaining about the "action" and "music" in the trailer is actually a bandwagon jumper. You just copied and pasted the one review that we've all seen over on yahoo, and decided that this guy must know what he's talking about. You haven't even seen the goddamn movie yet, and you're already condemning the makers of it! Guess what dipshits...this is the same fucking song that was in the first movie (that everyone now claims to love), and it's the same level of action  (so far) that was in the second movie, (which everyone initially liked, but not all of a sudden hates despite the fact that it's a better story than the first one).   Too exciting? Too much action? Too much good music? These are some of the most asinine complaints (from a TRAILER no less) that I've ever heard. If you brought this complaint to any other film, the person sitting next to you would probably slap you. But because it's "Star Trek" it has to be super intellectual ONLY, and make no references to pop culture? Please! Go back to 1966 if this looks too much for you. The rest of the world (not just Star Trek fans, but film fans in general) will want to see this precisely because of the elements you (and the one critic so far) is complaining about.

text: Was there any thought given to concept, narrative or character development? Do they even bother with screenplay writers any more? Or is the goal simply a montage of fun, visual moments and cute lines. Producers, you can still have subtlety, depth & nuanced ideas, characters & genuine emotions with sci-fi action. But let's not bother, let's make a dumbed-down bromance buddy action flick. I'm surprised Channing Tatum and Jonah Hill aren't in it. I predict fun, meaningless action with numerous plot errors & character inconsistencies. And hot chicks! But we'll include the manufactured emotion of a quiet, "serious" scene (with sombre music). For Star Trek fans, I guess it's true: In space no one can hear you scream.

text: I'll say it, a disappointing trailer. Too comical, have no clue what the plot is (not saying it should give it away, but we have like no clue what on earth is going on),  not even a hint on what the villain is going to be like, and the trailer has nothing distinctive about it whatsoever, just a mash of random action explosions and whatnot. No suspense either, just immediately introduces us to the Star Trek characters and next thing you know, a bunch of random explosion crap things happening. In terms of direction, this movie looks well directed and will probably have some pretty sweet action sequences, but the movie's tone and writing look AWFUL. Just hope the movie is better than this trailer. I'm not even too familiar with Star Trek, but I can tell, this isn't Star Trek, it feels much more like a Guardians of the Galaxy wannabe.

text: Historically, Star Trek films have done hardly any business overseas and the international market is where the biggest profits come from in today's motion picture rat race. Overseas markets do not want Star Trek: TMP, they want Star Trek: Fast and Furious. In order for Paramount to make big $$$ Star Trek MUST appeal to the overseas audiences. There are simply not enough Trekkie fan-boys and die-hards on earth to make the kind of money Paramount is looking for. Hollywood, in general, is making movies for a global market, not a limited crowd of Americans. In effect, all the negative comments being made about this trailer -- here and on other sites -- is going into one Paramount ear and out the other.

text: I hope the people who cut this trailer (and chose Sabotage as the soundtrack) are fired immediately.  This trailer is a poor follow up to yesterday's explosive Independence Day trailer that is getting people excited and hyped for the sequel (which is quite a feat since virtually no one asked for a sequel to begin with), unlike this trailer that has left people dumbfounded and uninterested.  Honestly, I have zero interest in seeing this film because I absolutely hate this trailer.  Motocross jumps, karate kicks, over the top stunts (especially from Scotty, of all characters), Jesus Christ...what happened to this franchise?!  Here's the thing, I'm not against action and adventure in a Star Trek film, it can be done!  Look at Star Trek: First Contact; this film pulls off being an excellent sci-fi action film without losing touch with the Star Trek franchise.  Star Trek Beyond, from what I've read in the trade press, and from what I've seen in this trailer, is nothing more than another dumb action movie that's part of the Star Trek brand in name only.  Paramount wanted a less "Star Trek-ey" film from the writers this time around....and by all means, they got it.

text: I can see why people hate the trailer; as it only showcases action, snappy one liners and rock music without teasing any kind of story line. But the actual clips are not that different from scenes in the last 2 movies. They had similar jokes and an abundance of explosions and fight scenes. Seems like more of the same to me. Bang average, albeit enjoyable, space action films.   The JJ Abrams films were nothing like the old Trek films to begin with, so raging over this one a bit silly. I expect there will be the same drama, villainy and story as the in the last two films. The Fast&Furious director probably didn't write the script here. But I guess he might have had a hand in putting together this trailer.

text: I think Star Trek has needed to cowboy up for some time. The best parts of Star Trek TNG were always the high action episodes where the Federation got together and tried to crush the Borg. I know a lot of people enjoyed the high brow attitude which Star Trek has developed but I just can't help loving this new focus on action. The best part of Star Trek: Into Darkness for me was the last 20 minutes when the Enterprise got blasted into swiss cheese, Spock wrecks Kahn on the back of a speeding hovercraft, and Kirk takes one for the team. Scottie and Bones were hilarious throughout. If I'm ever feeling the need to watch a bunch of stuffed shirts bumble through life while helplessly struggling against their personal demons I'd just spend more time at my job. The more humor and adventure the better in my opinion.

Thus far not one of the NuTrek films has ascended to the level of being basic science fiction, let alone anything that bears any resemblance to Star Trek. I already have generic action flicks at home.

text: urgh. *Puke* A fast paced, unintelligent throw up ride with tons of CGI and cliches as characters. It's like throwing a bucket of acrylic paint at the Mona Lisa and calling it art. Just another action flick with Trek jargon used to sell tickets. This is what you get when the marketing team orders and writes the script. When I look at the last two movies and now this one, I  just feel like Star Trek has been cheapened and dumbed down. Gone are the days where Star Trek was intelligent, thought provoking, ahead of its time. This is not the Star Trek of The Next generation, Deep Space 9 and Voyager  know. It is a caricature of Star Trek where flashy scenes. camera glares and sexy, good looking individuals get to be flashy and sexy and make bold choices and throw around trek jargon every 2 seconds to remind us that this is, in fact, a Star Trek production,  but it's not just like any Star Trek - this is a hip Star Trek. Clearly this segment was made to appeal to the Justin Bieber generation and in that regard I am sure it will be a box office hit.

text: Trekkie opinion.  Ok, yes...this makes me angry, but first let me say this. The 2009 Trek was good and I quite enjoyed it. Why? Because whomever was heading it up was aware of the rampant fans if they messed it up. So they made a plot point that would satisfy us. Aka...and alternate universe. They took great care in casting and even did some wonderful nods to TOS.  That being said...what in the heck makes them think that this is Star Trek?????  Star Trek is so much more than an action-packed flick (or at least that's how it was created it be!)  If you are truly interested in the heart of Star Trek watch these episodes of the various series and skip this wannabe movie. Really disappointed with what I just saw!  The Original Series: "Let that be your last battlefield"  The Next Generation: "The measure of a man"  Deep Space Nine: "Past tense" parts 1 & 2

text: MOTORBIKES? Ok..it's just a bad(robot) dream.. like i was sitting in cinema watching Kingdom of the Crystal Skull and the last  minutes showed an alien space ship leaving earth.  @Mr. Justin Lin: If you read this. Please, give me a chance to do the trailer stuff for you. I don't charge any money, but lets do it the right way. What i've seen here shuttered my heart to the ground as a guy who cuts movies for life and with passion and  love.  @Mr. Abrams: If you read this. I was one of the remaining guys playing your Star Trek ARG, ending up with a video message from the late Mr. Nimoy. I played it, because i trusted you. I already see that Star Wars: The Force Awakens is going to be a good thing.  Why in all god's heaven are you guys producing Star Trek: The Phantom Menance, Star Trek: Attack of the Clones and now Star Trek: Revenge of the Sith? Why Star Trek fans, nerds, geeks and dogs don't the Star Trek: The Force Awakens. What is the difference.  If there is a problem on communication between "What is Star Trek" and "I don't know what to do with it..so lets add some brainless characters and action" - then better hand it over to people loving Star Trek. Get people on board who spend a lifetime living and loving Star Trek. The new crew is fine..but why you're sending these poor guys on a "5 year, then the franchise is dead" trip?  Best regards, Tobias Löffler  Star Wars & Star Trek fan Lead 3D Artist

text: I enjoy these movies.  I'm excited to see this.  But not for a second do I actually think "Star Trek" when I watch them.  This is "Abrams Trek".  Abrams is perfectly suited to Star Wars, I'm glad he switched to that for sure, but I encourage you to do what I do: Don't think of this as Star Trek.  The new films are great on their own.  Good story telling, great action, great effects, good humour, just all-round good films.  But every last real Trek fan is either content with the original series, or wants a new Prime universe TV Show.  With about 25% (give or take 10%) of fans still waiting for a redo for the end of Enterprise plus a film.  And a film for the Voyager crew.  ...and something DS9-related.  I honestly don't know how Trek wasn't profitable enough to keep that train going.  All of this in my opinion, with zero fact checking.  Obviously.

text: Star Trek III: Beyond Ridiculous. Trek fans are used to being punched in the face but this seems a bit more below the belt.   The only reason star trek has survived 5 decades is because of the fans, and how do you reward millions of fans who have supported Star Trek for 50 years? Take everything about it that they love out, or (to paraphrase Simon Pegg) "make it less Star Trek-y".  This wont be a Star Trek Movie. This will be a Guardians of the Fast and Furious Movie staring the characters of Star Trek.  Paramount are trying to appeal to a different audience by (pardon the pun) alienating the audience they already have. The greatest asset with Star Trek fans is they are fiercely loyal, and have stuck with the franchise for generations (that one was intentional). They host podcasts, dress up as characters, have heated debates about canon and the next generation (ok, ill stop now) of star trek fans will do the same.   This different audience that paramount are trying to appeal to are fickle, short attention span types who tend to forget about something the moment something newer and shinier comes out. These people wont stick with Star Trek for another 50 years even if they do enjoy it, and lets be honest, the fast and furious types are not exactly famed for their enjoyment of all things Trekkie.

text: The first line of the opening crawl is "Luke Skywalker has disappeared."   The first sentence in the movie is "This will begin to make things right", said by Max von Sydow. Poe Dameron came to him to get the map to Luke Skywalker for The Resistance.   Max von Sydow's role is just a cameo, he has about 10 sentences before Kylo Ren kills him.   The Empire is now The First Order, The Rebels are now The Resistance, more extreme fraction of the New Republic, who are supposedly pussies. We only see the New Republic planet for a few seconds before it's destroyed by the Starkiller base.   Almost no one in the movie believes that Jedis and Luke Skywalker ever existed.   Kylo Ren captures Poe and uses the Force to stop laser blast so that it remains floating in the air, frozen in place.   Finn helps captured Poe to escape from the Star Destroyer only because he cannot pilot TIE fighter himself. Poe is an expert pilot, Finn can shoot lasers. They become friends.   Finn's "real name" is FN and four numbers. Poe starts to call him "Finn" because it's easier to pronounce. FN likes it.   After 20 minutes, we are supposed to think that Poe Dameron was killed in the TIE crash on Jakku. He reappers near the end (he ejected before the crash) to lead the attack on Starkiller base. He is not in the film very much. Finn wears Poe's jacket during most of the movie.   Rey meets Finn, they steal the Millennium Falcon from the junkyard and fly away. Han and Chewie catch them soon, followed by two groups of racially-stereotyped space gangsters.   Chewbacca is wounded by space gangsters soon after he appears and spends most of the remaining time doing nothing. Rey takes his place as Falcon's pilot, proving herself to Han.   Kylo Ren is Han and Leia's son. He is "Master of The Knights of Ren" but it's not explained what it means.   Kylo Ren's real name is Ben. He was trained by Luke but then turned to the Dark Side which was the reason for Luke blaming himself and disappearing.   The Starkiller base charges by draining suns and then destroys whole solar systems. The shot in trailer with Kylo Ren and red flare is the Starkiller base firing. Guess what, the Starkiller base can be destroyed by flying in her trench and shooting the "oscillator" or whatever.   Han meets Kylo at the Starkiller base/planet and tries to persuade him to return with him. "I am torn apart, father. But I know what I must do. Can you help me?" - "Of course, my son." They almost embrace. Kylo pierces Han with lightsaber. "Thank you, father." Dead Han falls into the shaft on the Starkiller base. Yes, he is dead. Most definitely.   Leader Snoke is the bald CGI bad guy with large scar across his face. He has snake-like movements but his body is never clearly seen. His motivation or origin is never explained. He gives orders to Kylo Ren and General Hux (who hate each other). Most of the characters don't know about Snoke's existence.   General Hux has screaming monologue in front of thousands of Stormtroopers: "We stand upon this mighty weapon you've built. Everyone will bow to The First Order. Today will be remembered as the last day of The Republic!" Afterwards, all Stormtroopers raise their fists. Very nice Der Fuhrer moment.   Fan service: Holochess. The levitating training ball from Episode 4. Admiral Ackbar. Rey living in the AT-AT wreckage. "1138" mentioned. Garbage chute and trash compactor mentioned. Kesel Run mentioned.   Simon Pegg plays an alien called Ankar Plutt who took care of Rey when she was very little and her parents disappeared. Now he runs a junkyard on Jakku and buys scrap from Rey. His face and voice is not recognizable.   Apart from Han and Chewie, all the "original characters" (Leia, R2D2, C3PO) only appear after two thirds of the movie, when The Resistance lands on Maz Kanata's planet.   Maz Kanata (small CGI gypsy) is the new Yoda and explains everything cryptically. Nobody understands her.   Han and Leia see each other for the first time after many, many years and have a touching conversation about their son: "You can still save him." / "How can I save him when Luke couldn't?" / "Luke was a Jedi, your are his father."   Kylo Ren and Rey have duel of wills. Rey wins, telling Kylo: "I sense your fear. You are afraid that you will never be as strong as Darth Vader."   Kylo Ren talks to Vader's helmet: "Show me the darkness. I will finish what you started, grandfather."   R2D2 spends the whole movie powered down and doesn't do anything until 5 minutes at the very end when it's discovered that crucial part of the Skywalker map is in his memory, probably but there by Luke long time ago. (It's not very clear but Luke appears with R2D2 in a flashback.)   Rey has a weird dream/flashback after she finds Luke's lightsaber in Maz Kanata's castle and touches it. The dream contains lots of quick imagery and short voiceovers by Yoda and Obi-Wan. Several famous shots in trailers (Kylo and his posse, Luke's mechanical arm on R2D2) are from this dream montage and are never explained in the movie.   Finn's origin (his skin color, who are his parents, why he hates the First Order) is never explained.   C3PO's red hand is never explained. In fact, there are many things that are never explained in this movie...   Both Finn and Rey have lightsaber duel with Kylo in the forest on the Starkiller planet/base. Finn is badly wounded and spends rest of the movie in a coma. Rey finally falls in love with him. (He loved her from the first sight.)   Starkiller base/planet is succesfully destroyed by The Resistance. We don't know what happens with Kylo Ren (who was there) but he probably survived. Snoke sends the message to Hux to "Bring Kylo Ren to me complete his training."   The last sentence of the movie is "May the Force be with you", said by Leia to Rey.   After the last sentence, there is an extended sequence without dialogue: Rey leaves the Resistance base in the Millennium Falcon with Chewbacca. They find remote planet where Luke is hiding (because they now have the map), Rey goes to the "first Jedi Temple" (which looks like ruins of some Scottish castle on a rocky island). Luke is there, dressed in old Obi-Wan style hood. Rey returns his sword to him. Apart from this sequence, Luke only appears for three seconds in Rey's previous flashback. Luke speaks no words in the whole movie and is onscreen maybe for 30 seconds total. He never meets anyone else than Rey.

text: Long time hardcore *Star Trek* fan here. I like to believe that I am objective enough to be able to see things (films especially) from different perspectives. And, although I do find that these new films aren't "ye old Trek," they still do offer some decent entertainment. Whereas the old shows delved deep into thought-provoking topics/themes, these new films just graze the surface while being injected with plenty of spectacle as substitution. And, from this trailer anyhow, this one does not seem to be slowing down in that trend. So, we'll have to wait and see just how much the "surface to substance" ratio has been affected before I decide on how I will feel about the new films going forward.  Are the new films bad? No, they aren't. They are entertaining. Are they as good as (or better than) ANYTHING Trek that has come previously? Definitely not. However, they are still good enough to watch and enjoy.

text: Ya know... When I saw that this trailer was uploaded I got this surge of excitement like I never felt before! I watched the trailer and I was jumping up and down like a 5 year old on Christmas morning! Never have I felt more excited for anything in my life and I've been in love with Star Trek for as long as I can remember.... Then I started reading the comments... No shit I, a grown ass man, started to bawl my eyes out as I was reminded of the real problem Star Trek has always faced and what will always hold it back... It's fanbase is incapable of introspection, critical thinking, unable to read any sort of cinematic language, and somehow pompous, so insecure about their own social and intellectual ineptitude that they spew negativity over anything that threatens their old conceptions (something that would make the eternal optimist Roddenberry turn over in his grave). Trekkies are the master race of sucking any kind of joy and excitement you may get out of life. I don't have much in my

Beat the shit out if the ship again, check. Scotty becomes an action hero, sure have been waiting to see the Yoda in AOTC version of Scotty. Did an alien just use the word frontier referring to how humans see space? Umm... 'Kay? So , basically just another version of what happens to sci fic when money and fashionable stubble are "what the audiences want." When are these assholes going to learn to tell the difference between "telling us" what we like, and listening to what we say we like. Oh and for all you dumbasses about to go photon torpedo on me about that last line, read the GD comment. Sci fic fans want sci fic, NOT Die Hard, meets SpaceBalls meets Point Break 2015.

text: I'm a fan of Star Trek and Star Wars more so on the Star Wars front (better marketing, toys, games, etc). I've seen ever single Star Trek/Wars related film, T.V episode, series, books etc... There is very little I don't know about in either of these incredible universes. What I can tell you is this; some movies will be better than others based on the methodology to reach different people covering different opinions and views. Not every movie made by either franchise can win all people's hearts and vote. What I do know is this, each time another movie is made, more and more people are aware of these universes hence more money for the creators and franchises. These movies provide jobs and entertainment = plain and simple.  I for one couldn't care or less for this trailer as compared to the Force Awakens trailer - two completely different levels of WOW factor for me personally. At the end of day, die hard fans will pick apart everything they want and they have every right too as they are fans. At the beginning of the next day, who gives a shit. By the way, I hope more and more films are made, it will help everyone with the Event. Cheers.

text: I'm sorry I had to dislike. Star Trek is not supposed to be a hyper-action fast-and-furious space action movie with a Beastie Boys soundtrack. It was supposed to be about deep space exploration and the discovery of the unknown. It was supposed to be through-provoking and intense in an intellectual way. Star Trek was a reflection about our place in the Cosmos. It was a quest for knowledge with adventure elements where we were supposed to expect the unexpected.   This... this is loud and generic Hollywood crap. This is NOT Star Trek.

text: Summary of the comments:  Fans: I want more of the same old shit that made for a dichotomy of terrible and good movies flip flopping like crazy and episodes that make less then no sense.  Movie Makers: Sure, here's a new spin on the Kirk origin story keeping most of the details fairly correct.  Fans: ARGH! THIS IS TERRIBLE!  Movie Makers: Ok, here's a sequel which pays homage to the movie you morons claim is the best, Wrath of Khan.  Fans: ARGH! THIS IS TERRIBLE.  Movie Makers: FINE FUCK IT! Here's a completely new movie that has nothing to do with the original series or movies at all except for the crew and the ship. And we're going to destroy the ship so you can't piss and moan about that anymore. In fact, we're going to make this movie so hard core about the people that we're going to introduce a warring faction of natives to this new world with the Enterprise being caught between, and likely needing to help settle the conflict, that in effect we're going back to TNG style Star Trek (the best Star Trek).  Fans: ARGH! THIS IS TERRIBLE.   Seriously. Listen to yourselves. You are just the worst kinds of fans. You're asking for movies that are exactly like the originals. News flash: The original movies all sucked. ALL of them. It wasn't until TNG that any Star Trek movie wasn't a complete ball of pure garbage.  And that's largely in part to the fact that Kirk is just straight up the worst Captain ever. He's basically James Bond in space. Which is terrible.

text: Okay kids, settle down and let me explain why J.J. Abrams is a genius. Star Trek, while being the hyper-generic "Dungeons and Dragons" of science fiction, was always made exclusively for this super-niche audience. Star Trek was made by talented artists and intelligent nerds, and that's wonderful. Kudos. However, it always lacked 1 thing: A director who just wanted to make a good movie. THAT is what Star Trek has always lacked. The best Star Trek movies were always ones where the director decided to do something different and add a little flavor that wasn't there before. Star Trek is bland. Let's face it. And let me explain what I mean. I loved Prometheus. Dense, complex and deep writing don't bother me. I loved 2001: Space Oddessy. Really slow pacing to set the tone doesn't bother me. What I don't like about Star Trek is that it's always been very bland. No personality. It was so generic, yet so inexpressive that each episode/movie just felt like a generic smoothie of science fictiony/Star Trekky stuff. This fundamental flaw is the very thing that J.J. Abrams immediately keyed in on and corrected. Yes his films have various internal flaws, but no script is truly perfect.  Just take this for what it is and try to enjoy it. J.J. hasn't let us down yet, let's just go with it and try to have some fun for the first time in 50 years.

text: Guess this is what happens when you lose J.J. Abrams as Director. Well, in not to long we'll know if the price was worth it. If STAR WARS The Force Awakens is as good as i hope it is then yeah throwing STAR TREK is worth it any day. But if The Force Awakens is a epic fail... Well then i'm going to be pretty darn pissed. And i'll get pissed at STAR TREK and hate on it because no matter what happens i'm a STAR WARS fanboy and therefor can't let myself hate on it no matter what they do wrong. Prais Jar Jar!!!! But for reals tough... This trailer wasn't any good. I mean like what the fuck happened? STAR TREK was actually pretty darn good! And INTO DARKNESS just blew me away! Having never really liked STAR TREK that's saying alot! Both the past films where great. But this doesn't seem great. They lose the ship.... That's one BIG fail. The style of the film is... Well it isn't really good in my opinion. Where are the lense flairs? And what the heck is the plot of this film? A albino fights them and then they join forces against Dr. Evilfish and win using the Bike of Awesomeness? Sorry... I'm not going to judge the film based on the trailer. But the trailer dosn't make it look any good. This just looks sad. The very first trailer doesn't have to be the best trailer. But if it fails to give a good impression then that's a flop... The first trailer has the most riding on it. This one failed in my eyes. Let's hope it's just a bad trailer and the movies isn't as bad.

text: I see a lot of people complaining that this appears to be an action movie, not a "Star Trek" movie which should be more "cerebral." Who says an action movie can't be cerebral? I like this trailer because it doesn't give away any of the plot. If you had a trailer that was promoting the more cerebral aspect of the film then it would have to give away big chunks of the plot and will likely alienate a large portion of viewers (remember this is a summer blockbuster intended to make money). A cerebral action movie is the pop-culuter equivalent of a philosophical thought experiment. Consider the classic though experiment, a train is about to hit and kill 12 people, you have the power to divert the train to a different track that will only kill 1 person. Do you divert the train and actively kill or do nothing and allow 12 people to die? Imagine if they made that into a movie, it would be action packed and cerebral at the same time.

text: You need really deft hands to make Star Trek films carry the philosophical weight found in the TV series. On the big screen, you are going to need to have heavy, gritty action and drama to satisfy today's attention spans. However, the Martian was quite capable of doing just that. Star Trek is very beloved because of its philosophical and exploratory nature. The reason I have had a problem with JJ is that he doesn't care about Star Trek and has a profound disconnect with it. He made action films and tried to piece together relationships in a flimsy manner. The writers he chose were not any better. The two movies come off as soulless and hackneyed scripted action films. There isn't anything that makes me  really enjoy and love these characters as I have from the TV Series.  Star Trek films have never been completely strong. The later TNG movies after First Contact were abominable. I didn't even like Enterprise the TV series at first but then when I did a front to back watching of Trek I fell in love with it. If you wanted gritty action with many philosophical underpinnings - you had it in that show. Star Trek is a beautiful world of very thoughtful characters and political, philosophical and humanistic proportions. It's why I feel so strongly about it and it's preservation. It isn't mere nostalgia. I am a kid of the late 70s. I grew up with TNG. I saw TOS later. I don't respect JJ for what he has done to Star Trek.

text: I am a long time Star Trek fan. The music for this franchise is extremely important to tone and emotion. When you play a song by the Beastie Boys (which really dates a movie) it makes it seem more forgettable. Star Trek is intelligence, leadership, big ideas and great challenges to overcome by a hard working crew. All I got out of this trailer was badly placed music with a bunch of show off stunts. What is the big issue here other than the ship being destroyed...again. So far this has a focus on destruction. I don't see any deep character moments. Better get it right Justin or you will never be able to look in the eye of a Trekkie without having to apologize for creating such a mess.

text: Why so much hate. You cannot do the kinds of stories on the big screen that you can on TV. To justify the cost movie companies want big movies. It's funny, after the 2009 movie came out people online were screaming for the villain of the next movie to be Kahn. The writers listened and then those very people reversed course and HATED IT! Now a trailer comes out for the next movie and suddenly everyone seems to be able to tell if it's good or bad from a few minute commercial for the the flick. Star Trek like Bond will live on even if the original actors, writer and producers aren't involved anymore, and to try to keep new people coming in they will change the course of Star Trek. Paramount used to scrimp on ST's budget, now they throw nearly 200 million at the screen and they expect some return, so instead of bitching about how much you hate, be thankful you still can go to a theater and see it every few years. Even if it isn't to your liking, at least it's still there.

text: The original vision of Startrek was to provide an entertaining space within which we could examine the problems our society is currently facing, and by placing it in the future with blue aliens those issues could be looked at more objectively, because everything was separate enough from us. However, accusing these films of forsaking that mission conveniently forget releases like ST Nemesis, which was already effectively a generic action film. Smart Trek films just don't sell anymore. I don't know if it's a reflection of what has happened to us as viewers, or simply the result of economics. Probably a mix of both.

text: My ideal Star Trek movie plot:  The enterprise is traveling with a eccentric, genius scientist on board, there are rumors about him not being completely sane, but Star Fleet has allowed him to get samples from a rarely visited, distant planet.  The second in command, and has two sex androids whom he calls friends, but because their brains were differently than a positronic one, and its hard to tell if the robots have free will or not, he has legal ownership over them, causing division among the crew.  After being forced to place stricter limitations on using the holodeck, the captain is working with available counselors to stop "portable holodeck" addiction among members of the crew, with failed success; there are posters on the wall urging people to seek help; people are becoming disenchanted with some of the decisions of those in charge and a few aren't showing up to their posts.  A stranded vessel gets picked up who are travelling merchants who seem both rich and seedy, and refuse to discuss what their cargo is, causing it to go on lockdown.  The captain agrees to take them back to their home since its on the way, but its later found out that they are illegal weapon dealers and the enterprise is taking them to their customers.  The old scientist is reclusive and has been seen dragging a tall crate into the holodeck every night, what nobody knows is that the crate contains a child borg, and the samples he is actually trying to obtain are not from a planet.

text: I just can't believe how you people are spoiled little brats. You just winnig and bitching around. For Pete's sake pull yourself together. Ok music is off and doesn't belog with the trailer but that doesn't mean that the whole movie will be bad. You don't know the strory behind it, neither character development. You just have bias toward it and you don't know anything. Yeah it's is utterly action-packed but that is a trailer. Scenes from the whole movie crammed in 1:34 minutes. That doesn't mean squat. Wait and see, than judge.   I'm a big fan of Star Trek and although I love the original series and movies, and TNG, DS9 I don't think J.J. Abrams did bad job at all. In my opinion he did excellent job and albeit his movies don't depict the core values of Gene Roddenberry they are still great. New look, new vision that correlates with todays society. text: OK so I am a fan since TOS ( yes I'm old). Back in the day I got attitude and refused to watch TNG from the start bcs it wasn't TOS. Then I watched and got totally hooked. When I thought about it, I kind of  realized I was going against everything Gene stood for. He wanted to challenge the world to allow things to evolve. Every series has had detractors and purists who rage against it and I can respect their love and defence but for ME I realized I was being foolishly unsupportive of exactly what Papa Gene was all about if I didn't give them a chance. Remember Elvis was the devil to one generation's parents and now he's considered tame as all hell.  I say if Uncle George, Grandpa Nimoy and even The Shat could support the evolution I can keep an open mind. The worst would be a world without Trek to my heart. Wish it was back on TV.     :) LLAP peeps to each their own ♥

text: Oh wait. I've seen this before. Remember when they announced Daniel Craig as the new James Bond and the entire world turned on him thinking he was ill-suited to play a legendary character? There were new websites, polls and entire blogs dedicated requesting his removal from the film. Only to see that Casino Royale was a kick ass movie!  Oh and when Heath Ledger was announced as the Joker and world bemoaned Christiphoer's choice. How dare he cast a pretty blonde boy who has only had a handful of small films, in this iconic role. And then first trailer came out with some shots of the joker and we couldn't wait to see WTF Heath had done with this character. He looked amazingly sinister and fit for the role. And then the movie came out and the world crowned him the best Joker ever.  Well I may be proven wrong, but I won't judge Lin till I have seen the movie for myself. After a too few incidents of been proven wrong I now reserve judgement till after the fact. I think you should too.

text: oh wow. A female character who's an expert in hand to hand combat and has an accent..... never seen that shit before. Hear me out for a second everyone. Can we diversify the female roles in action movies just a tiny bit? its like the writers copied and pasted Michonne from the walking dead, then changed her outfit to avoid a lawsuit. And theres about a dozen others exactly like her. Get past the idea that a girl in a movie has to be either a hyper feminine love interest for one of the main characters, or a hyper masculine badass who still contributes almost nothing, and accept that you could just make them a regular damn character. Think if captain pike did everything he did in the first two movies, but was played by a girl. the movie would be NO DIFFERENT except that it would add variety to the classic "mentor turned parental-figure helps out his favorite student" shtick. I mean its not like kirk was introduced playing death metal in his bedroom, reading a copy of playboy magazine and wearing the equipment from 3 different sports at once, all while watching Black Hawk Down, because his gender isn't a focus of his character. his character focuses on his goofiness, strong sense of honor, friendship with spock, and ability to rise to any occasion. So if the main character can slide by without the movie throwing in our faces that he's a guy, why can't the same thing happen with the token female character make it happen hollywood, it'll be awesome

"It was very action-packed," Pegg admitted to HeyUGuys at the European premiere of Star Wars The Force Awakens. "It was surprising. text: Beast Wars!! I mean... Star Trek! I remember the first official trailer for star trek 2009 was pretty much on this level of action movie tone and people were freaked out, then they released trailer 3? I think, which had a much more dramatic and serious and EPIC tone, which made people a lot happier. I really really don't think beastie boys was a good decision for a star trek trailer. It makes this movie look insecure about itself when it relies so heavily on referencing such a small aspect of a previous installment in order to boost it's appeal and marketability in such a generic way. They have a real opportunity to distance this installment from Abrams obvious Star Wars fetish he just couldn't resist shoving into the last two movies throughout, and I hope they take it in a direction Abrams couldn't or wouldn't, and embrace the plethora of content and ideas Trek has offered over the years and what made it special to begin with. Here I see the potential for a story about human ingenuity in a desperate situation, which, yeah, can be a platform for an interesting story if told right, just as many episodes of trek have done before in a similar way. The creators of this are clearly caught between capturing what made the abrams treks appealing, and what makes ALL the rest of Trek appealing, while telling a story the previous films didn't (presumably). not an easy spot to be in. I will say that Abrams had some really great ideas for the cinematography and ways the camera moved and flowed and framed shots,more so in the first movie especially. And overall I don't feel that I am seeing the same level of competence and artistry here in that regard. I have to be completely honest and just say too, this movie looks cheaper than the last two, way cheaper. From Chris Pines hair and makeup to the seemingly limited locations and overall toned down use of special effects and apparent lack of truly epic set pieces seen in previous films ( with the exception of whatever happens to the enterprise that shit looks serious), I'm definitely not getting the same vibe here that made the Abrams Treks appealing in their own right in terms of the epic scale and adventure. I just have to wait and see like everyone else, but I am sorta not thrilled about this so far.

text: On some level, I appreciate that Star Trek is still going and people are still watching it.  But this trailer concerns me. I do not want Star Trek and its subsequent adaptations to become nothing more than Fast and Furious in Space. Of course some will say that JJ Abrams Star Treks were just that, but those have some emotional and philosophical complexity if you look closely, and they exemplify Kirk and Spock's brotherhood.   I want to like this movie, but the trailer looks bad. Beastie Boys was a poor choice of music and it completely disregards the last part of Star Trek Into Darkness. What happened? Did they start their journey and get recalled or some BS? I realize the movie format is not as great as TV for the Exploration theme, but they could at least try something different than "enterprise/earth in danger, must battle evil villain and nearly or completely destroy the Enterprise." All in all, I hope the movie proves me wrong, but this was a poor start for a movie that already has an army of detractors at its back.

text: I'm probably going to regret putting this here on account of my inbox getting spammed, but here goes: to those who want to see the action parts of this, I applaud you. The same goes for all those who want there to be mainly intellectual material. In the end, though, can we take a moment to just stop arguing about how this looks like Fast and Furious in space or that they're happy that the old show is dead? Llet's all have respect for one another and move on. This is just a movie. Now before the hate starts, let me remind you that this is just a trailer. We have yet to see the full works. Maybe it has the right amount of both- which could very well happen as we have a new director. Maybe it won't. At the very least, let's wait until the movie comes out. And to those who's at that the trailers are there to spark discussion and that we didn't see anything but action and therefor there will be no intellect in this movie- would you put just talking in a trailer to draw people in to see a movie, or would you put the impactful material? I'll leave that to you. I bid you a due.

text: I know this isn't J.J. Abrams... but really, why do people hate on the 2009 Star Trek and Star Trek: Into Darkness, which were both directed by JJ? People hate them so much, and all they say as an excuse is because "IT'S NOT HOW GENE DID IT, IT'S ALL CHANGED, IT'S DIFFERENT FROM THE ORIGINAL, J.J. SHOULD'VE KEPT IT ALL THE SAME!" Seriously?! Thing's change over time, and sometimes changing things is good. And that's your opinion if the movies are bad, which I don't have a problem with your opinion, but the excuse, I do. "IT'S CHANGED!!" Just because it has changed from the original format doesn't mean it's a bad movie. Both new movies have a great cast, terrific special effects, menacing villains, a very good storyline and conflict, exciting action, and a wonderful soundtrack. Everything changes, wether you want it to or not. Get over it, stop whining idiots.

text: Sigh, another lensflare CGI popcorn fest with no science nor intrigue to speak of.  So here`s the plot: Ship sent to investigate some plot / rebels / others who are a threat. Ship gets whacked and destroyed. Remaining crew make allies from rebels who are against main bad aliens. yada yada pop pop lensflare lensflare.  On Science: I remember being a 4 year old kid and wondering how to make transparent aluminum. I remember being 8 and wondering how fast data could count, I remember being 13 and reading about our early attempts at bio-organic technology because of Voyager, all of my scientific interest and my knowledge of computing I owe to these years.  On morality, ethics, and shades of grey: I remembered being 15 and being horrified at what Ben Sisko did to get the Romulans into the War, I was actually, utterly, shocked.  A scifi show, teaching a 15 year old boy about the devastating and compromised nature of war and its horrors.   As for the intrigue: I miss wondering what was past the next star, who were the next new species, what was their culture, what was their history. I miss when star trek solved technical and social problems through investigation, analysis, and judgement, and every new character they met wasn't trying to kill everything.  I mean Christ, does anyone over in Hollywood actually give a crap about the core. Have we all forgotten these words so easily?   Space: The final frontier.   These are the voyages of the Starship Enterprise.   Its ongoing mission:   1)To explore strange new worlds   2)To seek out new life and new civilizations   3)To boldly go where no one has gone before.   Today it may as well be "to boldy go somewhere relatively local and kick ass"  I miss Star Trek : (

text: Yall are just complaining for the sake of complaining. Yes, I have watched the original series. Yes, I have seen the original movies. I think they do a great job of revamping the show that we know and love into a more modern standard to reach a wider audience. Of course it is "all action" and no thought or philosophy...they are not going to put that "boring stuff" in the trailer. They are going to put in all of the exciting action to get people to want to come see it but I am willing to bet that the deeper stuff that makes Star Trek special will be in there. This is not going to be "the worst movie ever"... It isn't even going to be the worst Star Trek movie ever. Lets not forget that The Motion(less) Picture exists so lets just all calm down and not criticize it too much for a 1:33 second preview that may or may not even end up in the final cut.

text: I'm a bit skeptical as to how this movie is going to turn out, considering how the last two Star Trek movies have shown heavy influence by Hollywood's consistent revival of old stories whilst attempting to appeal to a newer generation. The trailer seems more focused on the action and thrills, rather than the actual essence of the story but I'm not one to judge too quickly. In fact, this is only the first trailer, so I'm a bit confused as to why there is already so much hate when others haven't even seen the actual film. Don't get me wrong, based on this trailer, the movie looks like a visual masterpiece, although the common complaint here is whether or not the story will live up to the franchise's original reputation. At this point, I guess there really is only one question: Who is this film going to be for?

text: I like the old and new Star Trek, sue me. Into Darkness actually got me to go to a movie theater, something I rarely do and even bought it on Blu-ray, Cumberbatch was tight as Khan, and the first one was sweet too and very rewatchable. So I'm not going to jump to conclusions that this is going to suck just because the douchebag from fast and furious got his hands on it. Star Wars sucks, it's campy as fuck with all the muppets and shit, and good vs. evil black and white mixed with the juvenile humor and cheapens bushido (and specifically iaido which I trained in for 8 months).   Visuals do matter,  when it's actually combined with a great story, it's magic. We'll see if it sucks or not, but it's a teaser trailer, it's supposed to get your attention, especially with all the visual distractions around us these days. The teaser has got attitude, balls, and is obnoxious as fuck, and flushes your brain down the toilet, but its a trailer, not a book.

text: I understand what's going on here: everyone wants the new Trek to be like the old Trek. People, this is an alternate timeline, so there will be differences. We still don't know how many other races were affected by Nero's time-traveling shenanigans, and it might be more than we realize, which may contribute to all the action versus what we saw in the TV show. Also, the fistfights and photon torpedoes from the TV show were probably exciting to the people way back then like this action is to us today (although taken down a few notches, I'll give you all that). And who knows? Maybe all of the action will be justified when we find out the plot, and maybe it won't. But don't forget, Pegg said that the trailer wasn't like the movie. You never know. That said, I respect everyone's opinion. And as we all know, Star Trek has had its stupid moments. No one said that they'd be eliminated with the reboot.  But I still want to see this and don't think it looks bad.

text: Now, this doesn't look like a bad movie. But this quick, sudden, flashy, and intense in-your-face style doesn't really seem to suit the style of Star Trek.   Star Trek had its action, of course, but generally it was a much bolder, more dramatic, slower paced style. More based around emotion and intrigue, rather than guns blazing, jumping into a firefight and rushing headfirst into combat. This is more like the stereotypical action movie rather than the stereotypical science fiction.   Look guys, the emphasis on cheesy action is awesome and all, but save that for another movie where it would actually fit. A sci-fi with that type of style has great potential and I'd like to see it executed well, but you still want Star Trek to resemble Star Trek.

text: First of all, a trailer is only suppose to make us aware of the movie, NOT tell us what the movie is about.  Crew in danger, Enterprise destroyed, cool.  NOT Khan returns, damages the Enterprise, finds Genesis, tries to kill Kirk, submarine battle in space, Khan is beaten, Khan tries to destroy the Enterprise with Genesis, Spock sacrifices himself to save the ship.  We've all seen Star Trek 2: The Wrath of Khan, a cinematic masterpiece that few could ever top, that we can watch over and over again knowing full damn well about the emotionalism over Spock's heroic sacrifice and solid story with solid acting.  BUT guarded by the fact that Spock is going to return on the next movie.  BUT what so few seem to realize, or even spot because the new movies were not dumb down for them, is that they doubles the humour, tripled the action, and centupled the lens flare.... yes centupled is a real word, the very thing that makes Star Trek what it is is still very much present.  The only real difference is that the story and action are streamlined without stepping on each others toes, but the purists are tripping over their own feet as they try to keep up.  Poverty, disease and war are pretty much gone on Earth in the new movies.  It's the Enterprise not on a mission to save the people from Earth from their own undoing or restoring freedom to the Federation, but the Enterprise explore us, humanity.  Seeing our successes and failures, seeing ourselves as the crew of the Enterprise.  Seeing a world not as is, but seeing it what we want it to be.  Where we come together despite our differences not because of a common enemy, but a common goal.  They define Star Trek as much as wagon trails to the stars, and they are extremely easy to spot whether you are a simple movie goer, or a hard core Trekkie like me, who has been one for nearly 40 years.
