text: Wow. I'm really surprised at the comments and dislikes of this trailer. I understand a trailer gives us an idea of the film but trailers can be wrong now and then and we can always be surprised regardless of how good or bad the trailer is. text: Huh.  I feel like I'm getting different things out of this trailer than everyone who sees only the action.  For me, I get three things.  One, humor - a kind of humor that I enjoy, which stems primarily from the eccentricities of the characters.  Two, the setting, which appears to be on an alien planet.  This, for me, goes back to the original movies and series quite well, and it's what I missed in the previous films.  Being stranded on an alien planet and having only their brains and their guts with them to figure out how to get off while also dealing with potentially hostile locals.  And three, a new, strong female character, of which I am always appreciative, especially in films. I have always loved the various series and I grew up watching them, but I know I am not a real Trekkie like some, so can I ask respectfully what you guys disliked about the other new films (I read through some of the comments and saw quite a bit of hate on them)?  For me (I'm saying that a lot... haha~), I really enjoyed them.  I liked how they kept a number of the themes of the original without purely copying it and how they managed to combine action and high technology/SFX with character depth, humor, and a compelling plot/drama.  Which is all I can ask for in a good movie in general.

text: It's amazing how many people on this comments thread are forgetting that most of the 12 previous Star Trek movies are action/adventure/comedy movies FIRST, and Star Trek movies SECOND.  The very best Star Trek movies IMO are Wrath of Khan and Undiscovered Country, yet those were the two movies that pissed off Roddenberry the most!    The movie that perhaps most resembles Roddenberry's vision was The Motion Picture, which moves at a snail's pace.  I caught it again over Christmas and the scene where Kirk and Scotty approach the Enterprise is literally 5 minutes long.  It's the exact opposite of 'entertaining.'    What I'm saying is: this movie is no different than all the other TOS, TNG and Reboot movies.  Every fan knows that Trek lives and breathes best on TV, but let's not kid ourselves: it's ALSO a thrill to see starships on the big screen too, with a budget that can generate truly alien worlds.    This 90 second trailer is selling the spectacle but it seems to me that the film itself will really address, for the first time in any Trek movie, the dangers of going where no one has gone before.  I can only think of the TNG episode Q Who, where the crew first encounter the Borg, that similarly highlights the very real possibility that you'll eventually bump into something you can't handle.  I'm very much looking forward to seeing a film that fulfils the promise of the 2009 movie, whilst also the new TV show in development.

text: Dear Paramount, did you know that Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was a big fan of the original Star Trek series? Also, did you know that Dr. Stephen Hawking once had a cameo on Star Trek the Next Generation? These things were possible because the series stood for a principle that a society is united and work together in the future, dedicating their lives toward the pursuit of scientific discoveries and the betterment of humanity. In my opinion, if your "franchise" no longer wish to represent these ideas, then please just leave the word Star Trek out of your films and show some respect toward Gene Roddenberry.

text: #StandWithAxanar   Paramount/CBS have recently decided to file a lawsuit against a fan created feature length film called Star Trek Axanar. Despite their precedent of allowing and encouraging fan works to be created, Paramount/CBS has swept in well over a year after the Axanar project was created and crowd funded to call fowl. This is unfair, untimely, and stands against the precedent these companies established in regards to fan created material.  I hope all fans of the Star Trek universe will stand against the hypocrisy of Paramount/CBS. It doesn't help that their recent efforts with this franchise have been abysmal attempts to grab more money. Now they make a tyrannical sweep against a fan film that has a truer heart of Star Trek than any recent "professional" releases. Not to mention they file this suite not during the funding campaign, nor the release of the short Prelude to Axanar, but a mere 6 months before the release of the fan film and after significant expense has been spent on the part of Axanar Productions.

text: Well, the fact that William Shatner is not in the 50th. Anniversary celebration film has settled it with me. I will not spend my money for a ticket NOR even watch the DVD. I'm done. Pegg/Lin and Jung have no idea what Star Trek even is. I mean if you want the new crew to stand on their own, let them do it in a non anniversary film. I mean this is the 50th Anniversary of Star Trek.  Robert Orci had it right, his story incorporated Nimoy and Shatner both. Since Nimoy is no longer around that is all the more reason for Shatner. No doubt this is no tribute fitting for Nimoy.  Paramount has no idea what they are doing to the franchise.  They have lost their core fan base and this excitement on the new movie will not last long. Plenty of good ideas to bring Shatner in it is there, everything from the Guardian of Forever to the "echo" left behind in the Nexus like Guinan mentioned about her.  I mean Nichols, Takei and the others could have made cameos, for God's sakes man, it is the 50 Anniversary celebration. I'm done with Trek.

text: I think this movie is Beyond "mindless action".  Many of these comments are very biased towards this film and even previous films.  The first 2009 movie is a reboot that did a great job telling an original story.  Although it didn't go many places where no man has gone before it gave a sense of homage to the older series giving both the old and new trekkies/audience something to like and understand.  It's very clear that no one understood the meaning behind Into Darkness.  A sequel that focused on the Star Fleet losing their path since they were corrupted with revenge against Khan.   And Star Trek Beyond looks like they're giving what you all complained about from the last film, new worlds, new life, new adventures, etc...... So honestly what's the deal?  Is it simply because the movie is directed by Justin Lin?  Is it because you saw scenes in the trailer that had action in it?  Is that it?  It's too easy to criticize the work of a film without bothering to put yourselves in their place and see how it is like working with a production like this.  Not for just the director but for the other crew who work to make these films happen...  Not an easy job.  So far I haven't seen one legitimate reason why this film looks bad other than that it has "mindless action" and "the music doesn't fit".    Can't judge an entire movie because of one trailer.  We will have to wait and see how the film turns out when it hits theaters.

text: The problem is that though many people might like more action over thoughtful dialogue, diplomatic solutions and principles of humanism and peaceful exploration... There is a plurality of all of that. Star Trek is - was - a particularly wonderful and unique vision of the future which, if not originally suited for the conventional action movie audience, should stay that way. It's fine to have action flicks for the majority, but there is such thing as a tyranny of a majority and this has killed any chance of an intelligent, character driven and thoughtful reboot or sequel by taking the franchise away from the kinds of people who watch the TV series.

text: I'm not really fond of this trailer; mainly because it's not giving me a story to get behind. What it's giving me is a string of action sequences held together by one-liners and explosions.  That is not Star Trek.  Even though Star Trek takes place in space, it is about people and what happens when these people explore the galaxy to expand their knowledge. They push the envelope and each other. They care about one another. What we needed to see in this trailer was why and how the universe pushes back at them. Where is the conflict? Who is the enemy and where is the struggle of our heroes? Star Trek deserves to matter. This trailer doesn't make me believe that anything matters in this film other than the next action sequence.

text: Star Trek fans who hate the new movies have some valid criticisms, but the bitching and moaning about the new franchise in general is fucking pathetic. Okay, I agree that Into Darkness wasn't original, was annoying to watch, and didn't have many deep thematic elements that Star Trek usually has, but I liked the first Star Trek movie. I'm a fan of the TV shows, yet I like the new cast members because unlike most Trekkies, I accept that we are in different times. Star Trek is going to have more action because the typical philosophical material, while great, makes for a boring movie for general audiences. As sad as it is, the Star Trek fanbase isn't large enough to make for big box office numbers, and that doesn't cut it for a blockbuster film. The deeper themes can (and should) still be present, even if that means weaving a bit more action into the mix. The problem with Abrams is that while his first movie was perfect for reintroducing the characters and the franchise, basically doing the same thing for the second movie was where the criticisms that he shouldn't be handling Star Trek became valid. It's why he was perfect for directing The Force Awakens. He's good at pacing, visuals, energy, and at directing his actors, which makes him a great action movie director, but when it comes to deeper character stuff, I agree that it's better left in the hands of someone like Rian Johnson. Now, Jeremy Lin may not be that guy for this Star Trek movie, but Simon Pegg, a huge Star Trek fan, helped write the script for this movie. Everyone involved that's not Abrams (and maybe he finally knows why, too) knows that this movie needs to different. That's why, unlike the other virgin Trekkies, I'm giving this movie the chance it deserves. Good God. If you love the original shows so much, just watch them on repeat till you die and don't watch the new movies.

text: Just a reminder to a lot of people on here, this is a MOVIE. Yes, you can say it's not anything like the old Star Trek shows or films, because it isn't them. I personally enjoy these new movies, they have good acting and the cgi are incredible. But the purpose of an action movie is to entertain, first and foremost. The old tv shows were no different, but it was a tv show, which means they could go a lot more in depth with the Klingon or Borg. If you REALLY want something that can educate people, there are numerous documentaries on tv and dvd for you to watch that will do the same thing. If you think these movies are dumb and are for the narrow-minded, that's your opinion. You don't have to watch this movie. It's not as if we are living in Germany circa 1938 when everyone is basically forced to read mien kampf.

text: Wow you guys are pathetic. I mean seriously. If you compare every movie, or every new series that they create to the original Star Trek series then you may as well just kill the series now. It is proof in itself that the creatore of Star Trek made something special because they are still making movies about it. If every movie and every series was JUST LIKE the original then the franchise would just die, it would be boring, repeatitive, and have no life ion it what so ever. The movies are starting to move with the times, as we do. Yes there is more action in them, but that doesnt stop you feeling or connecting with the characters. It doesnt stop you from getting involved in the story. Yes maybe they could put some more memorable lines in there and maybe bring out the history a little more but they can only put so much into a movie. You guys are picking at the smallest of things, like the song choice for the trailer as an example... WTF is the point in that? Your honestly gonna sit there and bitch about a sing choice? Grow up already. Then your going to bitch about the fact that theres a motorbike in it and automatically link it to the director because he did Fast 7? again, grow up. Instead of camparing the new movies to the originbal series you need to see them as their own movie, you need to see them as the next chapater of the franchise, a franchise that is still growing, that is still gaining new fans. The new movies reach out to a new generation of fans, just like the original series did to us. I personally think its fantastic that Star Trek can go into new directions, take on new dimesions, and give new meaning to some of the most well known sci fi characters ever created. Chris Pine, Zachary Quinto, Simon Pegg, Zoe Salender and the rest of the cast are doing such an amazing job with their given charcaters and should be credited for their hard work not slated by bunch of Trekkie Fans that are clearly still stuck in the past. Get over yourselves and welcome to the new world bitches!!!!

text: At least they're no longer bothering to hide the fact that have no idea what Trek is or what they're doing.    Thank god this is the last one and the nightmare can end.  2017 can't come fast enough.  CBS will have their opportunity to prove they can do Trek better than this mess.  Here's hoping there will finally be good Star Trek airing again.    I'm getting tired of talking to teenagers and having to explain, "No, no, see, Star Trek actually used to be deep, thoughtful, compelling storytelling.  Some of the best hours of science fiction ever televised.  The Inner Light, Measure of a Man, Best of Both Worlds, Duet, The Visitor, What You Leave Behind...  Heck, even a couple Voyager episodes were good, like Scorpion and Timeless.  Trek wasn't really about phasers and warp speed, it was about stories.  Stories about hope and courage and decency and ethics, science fiction was just the setting, they were really always about heart.  ...Hey.  Hey, stop laughing, I'm serious."  With low-brow schlock like most of Enterprise, all the TNG movies, and the Abrams movies, how can I possibly hope to explain to youngsters what Trek used to be back when it was good, before the franchise decided to let it rot on the vine?    Help us, CBS-Kenobi.  You're our only hope.  :\

text: I'm a Trekkie since ST-TNG (as such, I can spout acronyms). My fave movie so far is First Contact. I measure that from the first impression I got from watching a movie, not from how well it's held up over the years. All this being said, Star Trek movies always suffered from the fact that they never seemed to move on from the TVshow format. JJ Abrams was right on the money, when he asked why ST movies always were shot as if they were on a tight budget and short deadline. The scope was usually as narrow as in a TV episode, and the decore was often only marginally better. Compare the warpcore and engineering from the pre-Abrams era to the new. Small sets, every bulkhead looked like plastic and plywood. Not exactly the feel of a huge starship the size of several city blocks. Especially later, this created a huge contrast between the interior shots and the CGI space shots. Yes, even in Nemesis. 80s, 2000s, 80s, 2000s etc To cut it short, c'mon people! The franchise had to evolve some time! So stop complaining that the franchise isn't as stuffy as you like it.

text: This Trek is going to be a lot of fun! I love the new films and I love the previous ones. There seems to be quite a lot of people thinking that Roddenberry would not care for the newer films post 2009. But from what I understood, Roddenberry was forced out of creative control for The Wrath of Khan back in the 80's because the first film was met with mixed reviews. Harve Bennett was given the reigns and Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan was a big success. People look at Roddenberry as some sort of amazing visionary. That dude cheated on his wife ALL THE TIME (a.k.a. ASSHOLE). So remember, he's just a regular guy, a horney one for sure, even though he created a cool concept for a t.v. series. That's really all it was, a T.V. show. Which means all of that shit is made up and doesn't matter. It's fun but by the end of the day I have to pay my bills, do regular 21st century stuff and pay off the toy Enterprise-A and Bird of Prey on my sons shelf I bought with a credit card. Could be bad, could be good. You could also just not be a bitch and be thankful for new Trek.

author: Thomas J O'Connell

text: It's a terrible trailer, trying to woo an audience who doesn't like Trek anyway. The fact that it's the 50th anniversary movie of this franchise makes this trailer not only bad, it's insulting.  Look at how Paramount teased ST 6 for its 25th if you want to see how respect of a beloved franchise is treated. Look at how Dr. Who and Star Wars are treated by people who love and respect the history of a show, and all the talented people who came before them.   Star Wars gets treated with all the reverence of a visit by the Pope. The Falcon is rebuilt in exquisite detail. Star Trek gets all of its history flushed down the toilet (except they keep reusing everything anyway for lack of an original idea), and we get an Apple store and a brewery for an Enterprise.  Since the ST franchise is now split in two by corporate buyouts - movies are made and owned by Paramount and Trek TV is owned by CBS/Viacom, we faithful Trekkies may have to give up on the film franchise. Hopefully the new series by CBS (who took the time and effort to restore TOS with new effects and do a frame-by-frame remaster of TNG), will be more faithful. Besides that, Trek was created for TV, and still does best in that format.  So the alternate universe belongs to Paramount. CBS/Viacom owns the "real" one. At this point I sincerely hope this is the last Trek movie.
author: J T Torgerson

text: I am 47 years old, disabled, and live alone. I recently rewatched the entirety of TV Trek... It was an AMAZING journey of insight and self discovery. But these movies you are making, Paramount... They just are not what Trek is all about. And that makes me very sad. I accepted the first Star Trek "shoot 'em up" as just a way to get more people involved into the franchise who may not be familiar with it. I gutted the 2nd one's premature use of one of the series' pinnacle villains to basically follow the same underlying premise as Star Trek 2: The Wrath of Khan; just accepting it as the price of having some form of Star Trek that was new. But when I saw a THIRD movie shaping up to be yet another "blow stuff up" Star Trek, it was then that I finally accepted the fact that there must be no one left at Paramount who has any sort of clout that remembers what Trek is all about. It should by learning about ourselves as we embark on that amazing next step out into the stars. While, yes, there may be the occasional blatant rollercoaster ride, for the most part, traditionally it has dared to ask the tough questions in clever ways. And I think that is what I am missing the most here: it's that this Star Trek isn't clever. It seems to just expect me to sit back and oo and ah while it makes references to itself. That is, itself from a time when it really mattered. And now with the whole Axanar lawsuit - and don't get me wrong, Paramount, I can kind of see where you are coming from - I just wonder if Star Trek finally really is dead? And in a day and age where the only real metric of corporate success is measured by growth, ironically it's all about money which is one of the very things that Gene Roddenberry himself had REMOVED from our future! (I'm talking strictly Federation, here) I guess it will stay alive in the hearts and minds of the millions - MILLIONS - still alive who will continue to make amazing fan fiction, which includes movies.  There are few things I really truly need in life and believe it or not Star Trek is one of the things that gets my immobile body out of bed and into my wheelchair each day. Now, here it is the 50th anniversary of Trek...I have made it to this date after growing up with it throughout the years...I have reached this milestone with Trek faithfully by my side in many life events and decisions...and I've found it dying. Please don't let the true spirit of Trek die.  I encourage others to tell their Trek story. Tell the world, and Paramount, what Star Trek means to you and why it's important. Take care, all.

text: I saw the first of these Star Trek Reboot movies a few years back and swore I would never see another one of them.  Not because of the cast, who did a good job, or the direction, production or action, each of them equally good.  What I didn't like was the fact that they were made at all. Let me try to explain.  I grew up watching Star Trek TOS & TAS  reruns in the 1970's.  I vaguely remember my dad watching TOS in the 60's when it was on prime time.  TOS and TAS were shows that reflected, commented and addressed the era and issues they were created in:  The 1960's and 1970's.  The characters themselves often were reflecting the people of that era as well and the way they thought, acted and reacted to situations similar to those of those eras .  I can say that TNG, DS9, and Voyager did the same for the 1980's and 1990's as well. But taking Kirk, Spock and the rest of the crew and totally rewrite the history of the franchise to have characters from the 1960's act, think and react to situations from the 21st Century is not only unfair to those of us who grew up in the 60's and 70's but its unfair to the young people of today.  Us old people(I'm in my 50's) deserve to have our generations historical treasures left alone while the young people deserve to have characters, stories of THEIR own which reflects THEIR era(Today).  I don't mind taking the Star Trek universe onward like with shows like TNG, DS9 and Voyager(Don't even talk to me about Enterprise) but don't rewrite history.  LEAVE IT ALONE! Now please understand that I'm not blaming the younger generation for this.  The kids today are, as a whole, a good generation with some incredible views on the world.  They also are a source of free tech support to a middle aged man who's smart phone occasionally does something its not supposed to do(LOL).  Its MY generation who's deciding to play it safe by rebooting everything and feeding them recycled mind candy.

text: This trailer is a disgrace to Star Trek's legacy. I am willing to make the claim that Star Trek has had a larger impact on our society than any other work of fiction created before or after it, and thus, it deserves so much better than to just become the latest mindless and boring high octane action flick whose sole purpose is to draw in the Fast and Furious crowd and make a mountain of money that would make the Grand Nagus envious.  However, I am still holding out hope that this trailer is just awful (like Simon Pegg says), and the movie itself is more akin to "real Star Trek". But even that hope is holding on by a thread, as this movie was incredibly rushed, is STILL undergoing re-shoots, and the studio producing it allegedly stated that they want this movie to be "less Star Trek-y".  I just want this movie to be over with so we can be done with NuTrek and hopefully move on to real, thought provoking, and inspiring Star Trek in the new series.

text: I could out-write any Paramount writer in 1 month,  I guarantee that. Yeh, I am a writer, I dont have the big connections, it is annoying to see people get paid a great deal for so little thought. I thought the 2009 one was alright and Eric Bana played his role perfect. These movies are like 5/10 movies to me, I think Nimoy saved the 2009 one along with Pike.  Star Trek is all about intellectual prowess. Not just action, they should of started where Kirk is a Cadet and becomes Captain in the third part of a trilogy. Losing Pike in the third act rather than the second, sometimes it takes a great deal of suffering and many mistakes to become a good leader, not a cocky kid. They seem to just give him everything so quickly and easily, they should of made Kirk feel fully responsible for Pikes death and Spock help him see the logic. Beastie Boys track is kind of stupid, its not essential, if you want to create a reminiscing event, use a similar event with higher stakes, not a song. I guarantee no one will remember that song by that time. This is Star Trek,  not Die Hard, its just a sheer example of an ego getting in the way of development by putting forward things that do nothing to serve the whole story.

text: Destruction! Loud things! Impossible odds! This just screams "formula action movie". This isn't Star Trek at all, it's a video game.   There are enough Transformers, Fast and Furious, and comic book adaptation movies to keep the adrenaline junkies satisfied. Can't we have one franchise that is just a bit cerebral? Somehow, Hollywood has incorrectly conflated "Intelligent" with "Boring". Do you know what boring really is? Motorcycle jumps. Car chases. Surviving fire and massive explosions by "ducking".   Action is fine, but every movie franchise seems to want to rewrite the laws of physics and human physiology. Suspension of disbelief only goes so far, and after that it's clear that you've made your characters invincible and immortal, unless you choose to kill one off for shock value. That's really boring.   There has to be someone who can write and direct something that's a happy medium between Star Trek: The Motion Picture and the rebooted Star Trek: The Running, Jumping and Explosions with Lens Flares.

text: A 21st Century motorcycle in a movie depicting far-out-into-the-future machinery in a far-out-into-the-future time scale? I'll watch it because I'm a die-hard Star Trek fan of the OS, but I'm not very hopeful after watching this trailer. I sure hope it turns out to be better than what this trailer doesn't promise it to be. Maybe it's the trailer that's not so good... I doubt. As for Spock now embracing his "human side," that's just crappy. It ruins so much with Star Trek's OS dynamic of Spock's logical decisions and inability to understand human emotions. If there is life in the universe there just might be species out there who don't feel emotions like we are familiar with. They might be entirely logical in their decision making. What a shame to not have a species like Spock remain Vulcan and logical. That alone makes it "not Star Trek." Producers are losing touch with what Star Trek was all about. IMO

text: Hello Everyone, I feel I need to post this. For those who might have missed it, due to a fan based film both CBS and Paramount have issued "guidelines" that actually destroy all the possibilities of anymore real fan based trek films in the future. If you would like to know more search for "star trek prelude to Axanar" and watch the previews and details about the show. There are many fan based films for you to watch and some are really good considering they are not made by a real studio. You will even see a few real actors are involved and the efforts have been made to have a very high quality of production. Yes, some not so much but its about Star Trek not production. Now please consider that for many years now they (CBS and Paramount) have allowed a few groups to make many really good (and some not so good) episodes based on Star Trek in many versions as long as they do not "make a profit" from the production. To actual start making the episode Axanar they had a fund drive and made over 1 million US Dollars so, CBS and Paramount sued them to stop production. Recently they released the "guidelines" for all future fan based films that are not only not constitutional points (like actors who worked in any trek can’t work in fan based films and vice a versa) but limit production time and costs in such a way that means no less than a clear effort to kill all fan based Star Trek films. Read the complete set of guidelines here: http://www.startrek.com/fan-films I ask all fans to get educated on these Star Trek fan based films to read up on this matter. Please learn the facts about the past films and the possibility of future for more of them. If you cannot agree that CBS and Paramount be allowed to force these guidelines on fan film production please help us stop them. Also please compare the way the fan films for Star Wars are treated where they even offer a public awards show for them. I, and other Star Trek fans are calling for a boycott of the upcoming movie and the 2017 series on CBS unless they publicly stop this and provide the fans with a reasonable and legal ability to enjoy others ideas of the Star Trek world. They have allowed it for years but now they are moving to kill them while hoping it won’t affect them making more money off Star Trek. So, let’s boycott them and stop the money they would make from the 7-22 release of Star Trek Beyond and the 2017 series planned to have one show on TV then the rest on a pay service only from CBS. If they see enough decrease of the upcoming movie sales they will obey us as the fans and workout a real reasonable way for them to continue without the idiotic and illegal current guidelines. I, and more than 20 people I know have agreed to boycott the new film unless this is fixed right.  Thanks for your time.
author: Alan Hamby

text: For all those who are critiquing Spock's human tendencies, please remember that they created room for this development by introducing a time traveling Spock who influenced his younger self. His mother originally lived a lot longer until Nero came back in time and destroyed Vulcan. This exposed Spock to his human emotions which, by nearly direct instructions from the original Spock, Kirk exploited to gain command of the Enterprise in the 2009 movie. This Spock has lost his mother and his homeworld at a point in his life where his hasn't had time to build up a strong enough wall to mask his human side. He has also explored a romantic relationship with Uhura during his time of crisis which further opened him up to his emotions. I'm not sure why everyone is so upset about the character development straying from TOS but clearly you're lacking a grasp of the concept of time travel. Introducing that one element into the new series has left all future character development and encounters with TOS villains like Khan to be unpredictable and therefore better able to entertain a new generation and old fans alike by taking us down an alternate timeline. Let's stop hating so much on all the changes and see where this new road takes us. I'm sure Kirk wouldn't mind seeing how his alternate self faired by striking his own path without his father around.

text: As enormous trekker i anticipated this with joy and optimism and while it is not disaster everyone thought it would be it is inferior to last 2 films. Beyond is definitely homage to the more adventurous classic episodes and is geared to broader audiences than last film and i can appreciate the change. Crew is once again amazing and chemistry is off the charts, adventure kicks into 5th gear and never stops, dialogue is witty and fresh and it makes you feel for the characters. It is also exciting, thrilling and always on the edge of your seat entertainment. What bothered me is how Justin Lins directing style doesn't mesh with star trek tradition and how god awful villain in this movie was. I mean the directing was really awful, there were moments where i just could not see what is going on, especially during the dark scenes. As for Krall/Edison it was the most lazy, generic and uninspiring way to go about bad guy and it just did not work. I did not care about him or his agenda. Overall it delivers as fun summer popcorn entertainment and i was satisfied when credits roll plus it was kinda sad when you say goodbye to Leonard and Anton in the end, may they rest in peace. 3.5/5

text: Simon Pegg breathed new life into this series and did a really good job.  I enjoyed it much more than I thought I was going to from seeing the trailers.  It felt like a Star Trek movie should.  The villain was a little bit too much of the tired trope "former ally turns evil and tries to take revenge" type, but Idris Elba at least portrayed him well.  The most enjoyable parts of the movies for me were the character interactions with the crew, though I did also enjoy Jaylah and her role in helping them find the USS Franklin, which seemed like a nod back to the Enterprise series, which I very much miss, so it was nice to see that thrown in.  I was really hoping the villains in this might turn out to be Romulans, which would have added more depth than the "former captain wants revenge on Star Fleet".  I'm really hoping you guys do something with them in the near future, as they were some of the most interesting villains in the franchise and certainly during TOS and TNG timelines.

text: im a huge fan of star trek tos, and I walked into this film expecting to be disappointed. I was so suprised. this movie was great. I loved it. I think that this was better than the first two. it is the first star trek   film I've seen in a long time that genuinely feels like a star trek movie. the characters feel more like they do in tos. the chemistry was great. I loved the writting, and the whole thing felt more alive then the other two. the call backs to the original were perfect and the humor was spot on. My dad, who really doesnt like the roeboots, really loved this film. One of things I always liked about the vulcans was the clothing design. I loved the long flowing robes. in the 2009 reboot, they seemed to have totally gotten rid of the robes. in beyond the robes are back. I definitely recommend star trek fans see this film.

text: *SPOILERS* Well, i finally watched the movie and did not really like it. I mean ok, i enjoy Kirk and co, but the plot was pedestrian at best and i've seen less generic villains in a Power Rangers episode. Both factors were absolute zero, compared to Into Darkness. And then we get the one-note hot alien babe we're supposed to drool at/feel for and who - sad shocker - likes rap. Did the director think only hare-brained high schoolers would watch this? (with no disrespect to Sofia Boutella.... besides, why even cast her if you won't make proper room in the movie for her dancing skills like Kingsmen did? All we get is some flat, inelegant combat).  And the scene where the alien drones form a literal wave and the Franklin rides it while playing crap music, leaving a trail of exploding enemies behind, complete with the part where the ship flies in the alien drone wave equivalent of the green room?  I really hope they pick someone else to direct the next. Take Douchin Lin and send that sissy boy back to his beach to direct Furiously Dumb 17 or whatever.

text: (Spoiler Warning) I like the twist about the bad guy. But I'm still irritated by a lot of the bad guys logic. "War is good because it makes us strong. Piece is bad because it makes us weak." Of course if you're not at war then you don't need to be strong except as a deterrent against future war. Having a strong military to prevent war is very logical. But starting a war to make the country/planet/whatever strong defeats the point. Then there is the fact that the bad guy is a bit of a psycho from being shipwrecked. But I get the impression he became an immortal king of the entire planet overnight. It really doesn't seem like such a bad place to retire on. But more importantly his new subjects had space travel. He could have probably left within the first week if he had wanted to. That part I don't think was ever really addressed.
